===Etymology 1===
c. 1350–1400, {{etyl|enm}} {{term|clokke|clok, clokke|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|dum|en}} {{term|klocke|lang=dum}} 'bell, clock' (modern {{term|klok|lang=nl}}), from Old Northern French {{term|cloque|lang=fro}} 'bell' (French {{term|cloche|lang=fr}}), from {{etyl|cel-gau|en}} {{term|clocca|lang=la}} (compare Welsh {{term|cloch|lang=cy}}, Irish {{term|clog|lang=ga}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|klak}}. More at [[laugh]]. Related to Old English {{term|clucge|lang=ang}}, German {{term|Glocke|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|klocka|lang=sv}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# An [[instrument]] used to measure or keep track of [[time]]; a non-[[portable]] [[timepiece]].
# {{British}} The [[odometer]] of a [[motor vehicle]].
#: ''This car has over 300,000 miles on the '''clock'''.''
# {{electronics}} An [[electrical]] [[signal]] that [[synchronize]]s [[timing]] among [[digital]] [[circuit]]s of [[semiconductor]] [[chip]]s or [[module]]s.

